            <div class=3D"feature-description">
                <h3>What are HTML entities?</h3>
                <p>HTML entities are small code snippets used in web develo=
pment to represent characters that either have a special role in HTML or ca=
n't be typed directly on a keyboard. These codes always begins with an ampe=
rsand (<code>&amp;</code>) and end with a semicolon (<code>;</code>).</p>
                <p>For example, the entity <code>&lt;</code> shows a less-t=
han sign (&lt;), and <code>&amp;</code> represents an ampersand (&amp;). Wi=
thout encoding, your browser might confuse them for HTML code rather than c=
ontent.</p>
                <p>These special encodings are known as HTML entities, and =
they help keep your markup clean and readable.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 1/3 Columns -->
    <div class=3D"one-third column">
        <div class=3D"feature">
            <div class=3D"feature-description">
                <h3>Why use HTML entities?</h3>
                <p>HTML entities are really useful when it comes to both sa=
fety and compatibilty in websites. Some main reasons to use them:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Displaying special characters:</strong> Sho=
w things like quotes, ampersands, and brackets properly.</li>
                    <li><strong>Preventing code injection:</strong> Escape =
user input to stop malicious scripts from running.</li>
                    <li><strong>Cross-browser compatibility:</strong> Keep =
characters consistent across different browsers.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoiding syntax issues:</strong> Stop speci=
al characters from interfering with your HTML layout.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Whether you're writing blogs, emails or code, using enti=
ties helps your content display smoothly and securely.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 1/3 Columns -->
    <div class=3D"one-third column">
        <div class=3D"feature">
            <div class=3D"feature-description">
                <h3>How to use the Entity Encoder/Decoder</h3>
                <p>This online converter is made for developers, writers, a=
nd anyone working with HTML source. Just pop your text into the box and you=
'll see the result right away.</p>
                <p>You can:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Encode:</strong> Turn characters like <code=
>&lt;</code> and <code>&amp;</code> into safe HTML entities.</li>
                    <li><strong>Decode:</strong> Translate entities back in=
to readable symbols for normal viewing.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>It works with <strong>named entities</strong> like <code=
>&amp;nbsp;</code> and <strong>numeric ones</strong> like <code>&nbsp;</cod=
e>. Fast, easy and super useful when writing HTML by hand.</p>
            </div>
